;; 13-networking-and-protocols.slat
;; Book of CS Curriculum — 13-networking-and-protocols

(chapter
  :book             "Book of CS Curriculum"
  :chapter-number   13
  :title            "Networking and Protocols"
  :author-lane      "lacuna-eng-audit-rebuild-2026-07-14"
  :prose
"(chapter
  :n 13
  :title \"Networking and protocols\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You type a URL into a browser and something appears on your screen.
   Between the keystroke and the pixel, at least ten things happen: DNS
   turns a name into a number, a TCP connection opens across three
   round-trips, TLS negotiates a shared secret, HTTP asks for a
   document, the server assembles it (maybe hitting a database), sends
   it back, the browser parses the HTML, fetches sub-resources, runs
   the JavaScript, and paints the pixels. Every step is a protocol —
   a shared agreement about how two computers will talk.\"

  :the-layer-cake
  \"The OSI model has seven layers; in practice we use four:
     - link (Ethernet, WiFi) — how bytes move over a wire or radio
     - network (IP) — how packets are routed between machines
     - transport (TCP, UDP, QUIC) — how streams are delivered
     - application (HTTP, DNS, SMTP, SSH) — what the streams say

   Each layer is a promise the next layer up can rely on. TCP promises
   reliable ordered delivery; HTTP builds on that.\"

  :tcp-vs-udp
  \"TCP: reliable, ordered, connection-based. If a packet is dropped,
   TCP retransmits. If packets arrive out of order, TCP puts them back
   in order. Slower to set up (three-way handshake), but you get a
   stream you can trust.

   UDP: unreliable, unordered, connectionless. Send a datagram, hope it
   arrives. No retransmit, no ordering. But no setup either. Used
   where latency matters more than reliability (video calls, games) or
   where the application layer does its own reliability (QUIC, HTTP/3).\"

  :http-basics
  \"HTTP is a text protocol built on TCP:
     GET /orders/4472 HTTP/1.1
     Host: shop.example
     Accept: application/json

     HTTP/1.1 200 OK
     Content-Type: application/json
     Content-Length: 187

     {\"id\": 4472, \"items\": [...]}

   A request has: method (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH), path,
   headers, optional body. A response has: status code, headers,
   optional body. Status codes are grouped: 2xx success, 3xx
   redirect, 4xx client-error, 5xx server-error.\"

  :the-honest-null-lens
  \"Networks fail. That is not a bug; it is a feature. the runtime's
   handling of network calls always includes: a timeout, a retry policy
   with backoff, a maximum retry count, and a plan for what to do when
   all retries fail. 'Honest null' — returning nothing rather than a
   guess — is often the right escalation.\"

  :scheme-code
  \"; A tiny HTTP GET with retry
   (define (http-get-with-retry url max-retries backoff-ms)
     (let loop ((attempt 1))
       (let ((result (http-get url :timeout 5000)))
         (cond
           ((result-ok? result) result)
           ((>= attempt max-retries) '(escalate network-failed))
           ((not (result-retryable? result)) '(escalate not-retryable))
           (else
            (sleep-ms (* backoff-ms (expt 2 (- attempt 1))))
            (loop (+ attempt 1)))))))\"

  :cross-refs
  ((see \"09-systems-and-concurrency\" \"why networks are the origin of most concurrency problems\")
   (see \"Book of Systems — NN-01-networks-fall-over\" \"the network-failure taxonomy\")
   (see \"Book of SLAT — ch10-signing\" \"why message signing matters over untrusted networks\")))
")
